My recent foray into pie baking led to two firsts: blind baking and blind baking using GRANULATED WHITE SUGAR in place of pie weights or dried beans.  Blind baking pie dough ensures a crisp, flakey pie dough that holds up to any filling. And using sugar to keep the dough from forming air bubbles while baking is pretty resourceful!  I always have sugar on hand. It‚Äôs the bag of dried beans that are scarce in my cupboards. This tip from Stella Parks @bravetart, weighs down the dough during the pre-bake phase of pie prepping and toasts the sugar at the same time.  Just remember to place parchment or aluminum foil on the pie dough before pouring in the sugar (swipe to last photo). The sugar is reusable and after the second or third blind baked pie you‚Äôll end up with a toasted, caramelized sugar that works magic in many bakes!

It‚Äôs all about üçê pears over here in my kitchen for the first month of 2020. Jammin this week with these gorgeous seasonal jewels.

I read that late season (October) pears when harvested and stored properly will keep for months. I guess that‚Äôs the case here. They even needed a couple of days to ripen.

Theseüçêare sitting in the bottom of an old slow cooker.  The other pears were sliced and roasted in the oven. Pics 3 and 4. They got a bit charred.üò¨ I probably should have done more homework.  I threw them in a hot oven and the sugar burned. Think smokey brown sugar pears. The slow cooker with the lid askew allowed steam to escape so all the parts of the fruit (except the stems) melted into a syrupy amber rose pear mash. I ended up combining both and put all but the stems through the processor, added the recommended lemon juice and preserved three pints of thick, amber rose pear jam in a hot water bath.

Having just returned from a three week, 4500mi (7500km) road trip to and from Colorado to visit our daughter, I had a productive few days in my kitchen to prepare for our traditional and vegan Thanksgiving fare celebrated with family and friends. I loved the challenge of coming up with vegan side dishes!  Cornish game hens for the carnivores and a plant based turkey for the vegans. I made hasselback potatoes (from our garden) seasoned with good olive oil, salt and pepper, an orange and ginger cranberry sauce, sweet potato casserole, a @donna.hay fig and herb brioche stuffing and a mushroom gravy. Most sides were vegan by virtue of their simple ingredients and others, like the sweet potato casserole, I adjusted. No one missed the dairy.  I made our traditional cranberry butter, roasted brussel sprout dish.  And from our garden, butternut squash, apple and onion pur√©e, nestled under the roasted hens.
.
.
Our vegan guests loved the vegan turkey from @threegirlsvegan .  In fact they turned leftovers into a vegan beef bourguignon!
.
.
The meal was divine, but most importantly was how grateful and thankful I am to have shared this Thanksgiving with loved ones.  Now planning the Christmas menuü§ó
